Text.Value: I... I don't know.
...and mirrored. Take it - you will find it useful. What you do with it... that will be up to you. Same as before.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong sweeps her palm down the length of the spear. It glows with ethereal selunite power.
EditorData.SFXTags: [KD] Magic Glowing sounds coming from etheral selnite power on staff.
EditorData.VFXTags: [KD] Magic Glow on staff with ethereal selunite power.

Text.Value: You have been forewarned for what is to come, but not yet forearmed.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong produces something - the Spear of Night.

Text.Value: They were seized by Shar's followers, same as you. Only you were to be remoulded for their purposes, while your parents... I sense they have suffered greatly in the years since.
When I laid eyes on you, I sensed a similar bond. You, tethered to two others, someplace distant.
It is a tragedy that the Moonmaiden's rite was perverted by Shar. Your future was stolen from you.
That wolf - that elf... Who was he?
*You feel Shadowheart's mind tug at the edges of your thoughts. She wants you to stay with her, to see whatever is about to be revealed to you.*
It no longer has the power to harm me, now that I've removed it from Shar's domain.
The Spear. How do you have it? I threw it into the Shadowfell.
Of course I am. And I can prove it.
I have to find my parents.
You may have once thought of them as comrades, mentors, friends, even lovers. But they will all be enemies now.
He is your father - and he lives still, as does your mother. I felt them, bound to you.
When I laid eyes on you, I sensed a similar bond. You, tethered to two others, someplace distant. Let me help you remember.
Perhaps I was foolish to spare you. It may have been better to remain ignorant.
Shar is quick to discard whatever she has no use for. I think you know that well enough.
I felt the Spear call to me as I took flight. Whatever Shar calls her own, Selûne has equal claim to. They are one and the same. Their power is matched...
That is him. He lives still, and your mother too.
*Rest beckons. Soon you will be in Baldur's Gate, where you must confront those who wronged you, and save those who were taken from you.*
Getting your parents back sounds dangerous.
That can't be. I'm an orphan.
Get to the point.
No, it can't be. I'm an orphan.
Thank you.
Thank you.
But now the veil has been parted. You know what must be done, I trust?
We've got other concerns.
You still wear your hair like that of a novice. You should change it.
I chose to do that. For the mission. To protect Shar's -
Your parents are with your abductors. You will need to return to their lair. But be warned.
Your mind is a deep, dark wood. There are dead ends, shadowy corners, lurking threats. I was lucky to be able to glean as much as I did.
I'll help.
There must be more you can tell me.
I have kept my word.
What... who was that man?
Shar's embrace is something that was forced upon you. It is not your true nature.
Besides, there are more hardships ahead. Knowing too much may cause you to despair, while a little ignorance may shield you.
One last thing: your parents have been in the hands of Shar's followers for some forty years. It must take tremendous will for mortals to hold out that long.
I think you might be right.
Close your mind. This is for her alone.
You were to receive my mother's guidance in those woods. You were to come of age. Instead, Shar's followers snatched you. They must have been watching you for a long time.
Perhaps it was just a mistake. A moment of madness.
You will remember this spear, no doubt? It was to be the instrument of my death. Now it will become a parting gift in exchange for my life.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong produces the Spear of Night, holding it in both hands.

Text.Value: *A long, sleepless night awaits. But come dawn, you will have reclaimed a little piece of yourself.*
And who told you that? Your adoptive family? You are not to blame. You were young, impressionable. They took you because they wanted to break and remake you.
We are. Good fortune on your road ahead. It will not be easy, but it will certainly be enlightening.
*Your mind joins with Shadowheart's. Something pulls at you both, bringing you elsewhere...*
*You remember that it is a common rite amongst Selûne's followers to send their children off into the woods to find their way home. Perhaps this time it had gone awry.*
A debt repaid. You gave me my life back. Now go and claim your own.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong mimes handing over the spear to Avatar SH, who puts it away.

Text.Value: You claimed to know something about me - you knew about the wolves. Tell me everything.
My heritage? What are you talking about?
*She speaks pure heresy, or so you would have once thought. But you can deny it no longer - a new presence empowers you. You felt it ever since the Shadowfell. Selûne.*
First Selûne's blessing, and now her gifts. If only the old me could see this...
Your parents both followed the Moonmaiden. I could sense their faith, even in a brief glimpse of the past.
Shar may seek to thwart you in that - if she cannot control you, she can at least seek to deny you your past.
I am a daughter of Selûne - we illuminate darkness. We do not not create it.
There are always other concerns. Let Shadowheart at least be forewarned.
...and mirrored. Take it - you will need it. But what you do with it... that will be up to you. Same as before.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong sweeps her palm down the length of the spear. It glows with ethereal selunite power.

Text.Value: *A memory appears at the forefront of your mind.*
You already know who he is. Did you not see yourself in him? Do you not recognise your own blood?
Yes, a pain that I understand all too well.
I have to find my parents.
Perhaps this isn't a good idea.
I just want to remember what I lost.
The natural conclusion is that you are no true Sharran, and never were.
The elf you saw was your father. He tried to stop them, but failed.
You were to receive Selûne's guidance in those woods. You were to come of age. Instead, Shar's followers snatched you. They must have been watching you for a long time.
They're alive? How? Where?
The Spear of Night? I thought that was cast into the Shadowfell.
What do you know about me? You spoke of my past, being chased by wolves - I told no one about that...
How do I know this isn't some trick? You could have tampered with my memories.
*You remember that it is a common rite amongst Selûne's followers to send their children off into the woods to find their way home. Perhaps this time it had gone awry.*
...Until you weren't. Do you think it was but a brief lapse? A moment of madness? No. I think you finally listened to your heart.
You will have to face your abductors in their very lair, in Baldur's Gate.
No. A moment of clarity. You finally listened to yourself, and stopped resisting your true nature.
See that your parents' sacrifices are not in vain: allow the Moonmaiden to guide you at last.
*...It seems that one child never came back. She was taken.*
Do not pine for the nightmare now that you are finally awake.
Come now. I do not believe you did not suspect something was amiss. No true Sharran would have hesitated to skewer my heart.
You claimed to know something about me - you knew about the wolves. Tell me everything.
When you freed me from the Shadowfell, you severed a bond between me and that dog, Thorm. A bond of pain - his, inflicted on me.
This is not the time for symbolic gestures. You must stay focused.
Does this mean you're a Selûnite?
...Almost no one. But I certainly didn't share that with you.
But I felt it call to me as I took flight. Whatever Shar calls her own, Selûne has equal claim to. They are one and the same. Their power is matched...
That can't be. I'm an orphan.
Shar's weapon? Surely it's useless now.
For her purposes, perhaps. Shar is quick to discard whatever she has no use for. I think you know that well enough.
Whatever you have to say, just say it.
*Something sparks in your memory. Teachings about Selûnite rites of passage, about how they would abandon their children out in the wilds and force them to find their way home...*
Let me help you remember so there will be no doubt.
It is time we spoke about your heritage. There is a debt I must repay.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: NS cocks her head as she looks at SH in curiosity, taking in her altered appearance post-Shar's wrath.

Text.Value: I'll need every advantage, it seems... Thank you.
Forget her. She was forged by lies. Be guided only by who you have become.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Nightsong mimes handing over the spear to Avatar SH, who puts it away.

Text.Value: I was able to retrieve it, before it sank too far into Shar's umbral domain.
There is nothing I can tell you that you do not already know yourself. They trained you well, trained you hard. Chiselled away any part of you that did not fit their plan. They made you forget.
Forget her. She was forged by lies. Be guided only by who you have become.
There is one more way in which I can help you. You have been forewarned, and now you shall be forearmed.
That is how Shar wished it to be. She robbed you of your childhood, all to spite her twin.
*Pain surges from the wound on your hand... but no memory comes with it - no lesson. Just agony.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shadowheart reacts to the pain of the incurable wound in her right hand. She raises the hand and grimaces in pain. After a brief moment the pain passes and she lowers her hand, face relaxing, returning to default pose.

Text.Value: My father? That was him?
There must be more you can tell me.
When you freed me, you severed a bond between me and that dog, Thorm. A bond of pain - his, inflicted on me.
There is nothing I can tell you that you do not already know yourself. They trained you well, trained you hard. Chiselled away any part of you that did not fit their plan. They made you forget.
What life? The lie you've led until this moment? Confront the past, or your future is nothing but a coward's charade.
That can't be. I was always loyal to Shar.
Shar is quick to discard whatever she has no use for. I think you know that well enough.
*You feel Shadowheart's mind tug at the edges of your own. You know this sensation. She wants you to see whatever is about to be revealed.*
Shar torments you still. What a spiteful creature she is. This will not stop until you take action.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Small shake of the head. Empathy for SH aftter seeing her be tormented with magic pain by Shar.
EditorData.NodeContext: Reacting to Shadowheart having just been inflicted with a spasm of magic pain. Empathy towards SH. Scorn for Shar.

Text.Value: I'm going to make them pay for what they did to me.
Shar toys with you still. What a spiteful creature she is. This will not stop until you take action.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Small shake of the head. Empathy for SH aftter seeing her be tormented with magic pain by Shar.
EditorData.NodeContext: Reacting to Shadowheart having just been inflicted with a spasm of magic pain. Empathy towards SH. Scorn for Shar.

Text.Value: See that their sacrifices are not in vain: allow the Moonmaiden to guide you at last.
It seems we're even.
My parents. I need to save them.
A debt repaid. You returned my life unto me. Now go and claim your own.
Careful - isn't that thing supposed to be able to kill you?
You already know. Did you not see yourself in him? Do you not recognise your own blood?
I thought that was lost in the Shadowfell. How do you have it?
I'm sorry for your parents, but we have other concerns.
*Take action, yes... but freeing your parents will take time. Perhaps there is something more immediate you can do - something symbolic, to put Shar behind you for good.*
You may have once thought of them as comrades, mentors, friends, even lovers. They will all be enemies now.
I thought that was lost in the Shadowfell. How do you have it?
And who told you that? Your adoptive family? You are not to blame. You were young, impressionable. They took you because they wanted to break and remake you.
Your parents both followed the Moonmaiden. I could sense their faith, even in a brief glimpse of the past.
- secrets. Yes, yes. That is an old song, girl. Your goddess cares more for her precious secrets than she does her devotees.

EditorData.NodeContext: Interrupting Shadowheart to finish her sentence for her.

Text.Value: It is a tragedy that the Moonmaiden's rite was perverted by Shar. Your future was stolen from you.
That can't be. I was always loyal to Shar.
I just want to move on with my life.
But I am not here to convince you, only show you a path. Whether you follow it or not is up to you.
But you are a child no longer. You are a woman. One who knows what must be done.
Open your mind to that sensation.
I have kept my word. My guidance in exchange for my freedom.
*You remember sermons about Selûnite rites of passage, about how they would abandon their children out in the wilds and force them to find their way home...*
First Selûne's blessing, and now her gifts. If only the old me could see this...
Ngh... it hurts...

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shadowheart reacts to the pain of the incurable wound in her right hand. She raises the hand and grimaces in pain. After a brief moment the pain passes and she lowers her hand, face relaxing, returning to default pose.

Text.Value: You will have to face your abductors in their very lair, in Baldur's Gate.
That is for Shadowheart to decide.
I... I don't know what to say. I don't know these people.
Accept the Spear silently.
I'll need every advantage, it seems... Thank you.
If you want to remember, you will have to face your abductors in their very lair, in Baldur's Gate.
The elf you saw was your father. He tried to stop you being seized by Shar's agents, but failed.
Observe silently.
That wolf - that elf... Who was he?
That was a Selûnite ritual, wasn't it? So that means...
But you are a child no longer. You are a woman. One who knows what must be done.

Synopsis: Nightsong speaks with Shadowheart about Shadowheart's parents, causing Shadowheart to remember the truth. Shadowheart reflects that she needs to recover her memories in Baldur's Gate. Nightsong gives Shadowheart an artifact and a blessing.
